  "text": "## Graceful Shutdown Signal Handling Analysis\n\n### Prometheus (prometheus/prometheus)\n\nPrometheus implements comprehensive graceful shutdown in `cmd/prometheus/main.go` through a termination handler that coordinates multiple shutdown pathways. The signal handler registration uses Go's standard `signal.Notify(term, os.Interrupt, syscall.SIGTERM)` to capture both SIGINT and SIGTERM signals on a buffered channel (approximately lines 1450-1475).\n\nThe shutdown mechanism leverages the `oklog/run.Group` library to manage graceful termination of interconnected components. The critical cleanup ordering enforces a sequence that prevents data corruption: (1) Web handler stops first to prevent new requests, (2) Scrape manager halts to stop writing to storage, (3) Storage/TSDB closes to flush pending writes, (4) Rule manager stops. This ordering ensures storage isn't closed while scrapers actively write data. The implementation includes multiple shutdown triggers: OS signals (SIGTERM/SIGINT), web service requests, and internal cancellation signals, with proper coordination through channel closure and context cancellation.\n\nReferences:\n- [prometheus/cmd/prometheus/main.go - main branch](https://github.com/prometheus/prometheus/blob/main/cmd/prometheus/main.go)\n- [Anatomy of Graceful Shutdown: Part 5](https://mrlokans.work/posts/anatomy-of-graceful-shutdown-part-5/)\n\n### Kubernetes (kubernetes/apiserver and kubernetes/kubernetes)\n\nKubernetes implements signal handling at two levels:\n\n**1. Core Signal Handler (kubernetes/apiserver repository):**\nThe `pkg/server/signal.go` file in the kubernetes/apiserver repository contains the fundamental signal handling logic with two key functions:\n\n- `SetupSignalHandler()`: Returns a channel that closes when SIGTERM or SIGINT is received\n- `SetupSignalContext()`: The core implementation that creates a context and registers signal handlers using `signal.Notify(shutdownHandler, shutdownSignals...)` for SIGTERM and SIGINT on a buffered channel with capacity 2\n\nThe implementation features a two-signal protection pattern: the first signal triggers graceful shutdown by canceling the context, allowing the application to perform cleanup; if a second signal is received, the program immediately calls `os.Exit(1)` to force termination. This prevents indefinite hanging during shutdown. The single-call enforcement via `close(onlyOneSignalHandler)` ensures only one signal handler is registered.\n\n**2. Server Integration (kubernetes/kubernetes):**\nBoth the kube-apiserver (`cmd/kube-apiserver/app/server.go`) and kubelet (`cmd/kubelet/app/server.go`) call `genericapiserver.SetupSignalContext()` to create a shutdown context. The kube-apiserver uses `server.Shutdown()` to gracefully terminate HTTP connections without dropping bytes. The kubelet uses the context in its main `run()` function, monitoring `<-ctx.Done()` to initiate graceful termination. Cleanup ordering in the kubelet includes: health checker startup, Kubernetes API client initialization, container manager setup, event recorder establishment, kubelet startup, systemd readiness notification, and finally waiting for context cancellation.\n\nReferences:\n- [kubernetes/apiserver/pkg/server/signal.go - master branch](https://github.com/kubernetes/apiserver/blob/master/pkg/server/signal.go)\n- [kubernetes/cmd/kube-apiserver/app/server.go - master branch](https://github.com/kubernetes/kubernetes/blob/master/cmd/kube-apiserver/app/server.go)\n- [kubernetes/cmd/kubelet/app/server.go - master branch](https://github.com/kubernetes/kubernetes/blob/master/cmd/kubelet/app/server.go)\n\n### Grafana (grafana/grafana)\n\nGrafana uses a delegated signal handling architecture where signal registration occurs in parent initialization functions rather than the main entry point. The `pkg/cmd/grafana-server/main.go` file is minimal (11 lines), containing only `os.Exit(cmd.RunGrafanaCmd(\"server\"))` which delegates to the cmd utility package.\n\nThe graceful shutdown is implemented through two key files:\n\n**1. Server Shutdown (`pkg/server/server.go`):**\nThe `Shutdown(ctx context.Context, reason string)` method handles termination using a `sync.Once` to ensure single execution. It delegates to `managerAdapter.Shutdown()` to terminate background services, logs the shutdown reason, and implements context-based timeout protection. Callers can specify timeout duration when invoking `Shutdown()`.\n\n**2. HTTP Server Implementation (`pkg/api/http_server.go`):**\nThe `Run()` method implements graceful shutdown through context cancellation. A goroutine monitors the context and, when cancelled (triggered by external signal handlers), calls `httpSrv.Shutdown(context.Background())` to gracefully close active connections. The actual signal handler registration for SIGTERM/SIGINT occurs in a parent initialization function that creates and passes the context to `Run()`, following a pattern that separates signal handling concerns from HTTP server concerns.\n\nReferences:\n- [grafana/pkg/cmd/grafana-server/main.go - main branch](https://github.com/grafana/grafana/blob/main/pkg/cmd/grafana-server/main.go)\n- [grafana/pkg/server/server.go - main branch](https://github.com/grafana/grafana/blob/main/pkg/server/server.go)\n- [grafana/pkg/api/http_server.go - main branch](https://github.com/grafana/grafana/blob/main/pkg/api/http_server.go)\n\n## Summary\n\nAll three projects implement graceful SIGTERM/SIGINT shutdown but with different architectural patterns:\n- **Prometheus** uses explicit signal.Notify() with oklog/run.Group for coordinated component shutdown\n- **Kubernetes** uses a centralized SetupSignalContext() pattern with two-signal protection in its apiserver package\n- **Grafana** uses context-based delegation where signal handlers are registered in parent functions, allowing flexible shutdown coordination\n\nCommon patterns across all three include: (1) signal.Notify() for SIGTERM/SIGINT registration, (2) context cancellation for propagating shutdown signals, (3) graceful HTTP server shutdown without dropping connections, and (4) ordered cleanup of dependent components to prevent data corruption during termination."
}

